Afrioo, th'e south-west wind. —sub sinistra: i.e. he had drifted to the north-east (see map).

Caesar weighed anchor at sunset (about 8 nm). A gentle breeze was then blowing from the S-W.; but at the same time a tidal current was setting towards the S.W. Under the impulse oi these two forces, the fleet kept a north-westerly course until about midnight. The wind then died down, and the current also began to set in the opposite direction (NME) With this current the Romans drined, and at dawn the British coast appeared on their left. They had passed by (relictam) the North Foreland, aud were drifting sarther away from the land. But at about this time (5 mm.) the tide changed, and the crurent again began to flow towards the S.W. With its help, and that of the oars, the fleet now began to move towards the land, aiming to reach the same point that had been found in the previous expedition to be the most convenient for debarking. Here they arrived at about noon (Gdler).
